  "prompt": "How many 3-digit numbers can be formed using only 1, 2, 3?",
  "response": "To determine the number of 3-digit numbers that can be formed using the digits 1, 2, and 3, we need to consider that each digit can be used more than once.\n\nA 3-digit number can be written as \\( \\overline{abc} \\), where \\( a \\), \\( b \\), and \\( c \\) are digits chosen from the set \\(\\{1, 2, 3\\}\\).\n\nFor each digit:\n\n- There are 3 choices for \\( a \\).\n- There are 3 choices for \\( b \\).\n- There are 3 choices for \\( c \\).\n\nSince the choices are independent, the total number of combinations is given by multiplying the number of choices for each digit:\n\n\\[ 3 \\times 3 \\times 3 = 27 \\]\n\nSo, there are 27 different 3-digit numbers that can be formed using only the digits 1, 2, and 3.",
